In C++, `std::vector` cannot hold references directly. If you want to store references in a container, you can use `std::reference_wrapper` provided by the `<functional>` header.

Here is an example of how you can store references of string variables using `std::reference_wrapper`:

```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <functional>
#include <string>

std::string mIpAprilSideOSC = "127.0.0.1";
std::string mPortAprilSideOSC = "8080";
std::string mPathAprilOSC = "/path1";

std::vector<std::reference_wrapper<std::string>> _loadInto {mIpAprilSideOSC, mPortAprilSideOSC, mPathAprilOSC, mPathAprilOSC};
```

By using `std::reference_wrapper`, you can store references to string variables in the vector `_loadInto`.

