Here is an example of using try-catch block in C++ to handle exceptions:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    try {
        int num1 = 10;
        int num2 = 0;

        if (num2 == 0) {
            throw std::runtime_error("Divide by zero exception");
        }

        int result = num1 / num2;
        std::cout << "Result: " << result << std::endl;
    } catch (const std::exception& e) {
        std::cerr << "Exception caught: " << e.what() << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we are attempting to divide `num1` by `num2`, and if `num2` is 0, we throw a `std::runtime_error` with a message "Divide by zero exception". This exception is caught in the `catch` block, and the error message is displayed.

Yes, if you use `std::ofstream` in C++ to open a file for writing and the file does not exist, the file will be created automatically. If the file already exists, it will be opened and its contents will be truncated (i.e., the file will be cleared) unless specified otherwise.

Here is an example of `std::ofstream` creating a file if it does not already exist:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>

int main() {
    std::ofstream outfile("example.txt");

    if (outfile.is_open()) {
        outfile << "Hello, World!\n";
        outfile.close();
        std::cout << "File created and written successfully." << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cerr << "Error opening file." << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, opening `"example.txt"` using `std::ofstream` will create the file if it does not exist, and then write "Hello, World!" to the file.

When using the `protected` access specifier during inheritance in C++, the protected members of the base class become protected members of the derived class. This means that these members in the base class are accessible within the derived class and its subclasses, but not directly accessible outside the hierarchy.

Here is an example to demonstrate how `protected` inheritance works in C++:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

class Base {
protected:
    int protectedMember;
};

class Child : protected Base {
public:
    void setProtectedMember(int value) {
        protectedMember = value; // Accessible within Child
    }

    int getProtectedMember() {
        return protectedMember; // Accessible within Child
    }
};

int main() {
    Child obj;
    obj.setProtectedMember(42);
    std::cout << "Protected member in Child: " << obj.getProtectedMember() << std::endl;

    // obj.protectedMember = 100; // Error: Cannot access protected member directly from outside the class or derived classes

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, `Child` inherits `protected`ly from `Base`, which means that the `protectedMember` in `Base` becomes a protected member in `Child`. The `protectedMember` can be accessed within methods of `Child`, but not from outside, as shown in the `main` function where attempting to access `protectedMember` directly gives an error.

When inheriting using the `protected` access specifier in C++, the `public` members of the base class will become `protected` members in the derived class. This means that the `public` members can be accessed within the derived class and its subclasses, but not directly accessible from outside the hierarchy.

Here's an example to illustrate how `public` members are treated when inheriting with `protected` specifier:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

class Base {
public:
    int publicMember;
};

class Child : protected Base {
public:
    void setPublicMember(int value) {
        publicMember = value; // Accessible within Child
    }

    int getPublicMember() {
        return publicMember; // Accessible within Child
    }
};

int main() {
    Child obj;
    obj.setPublicMember(42);
    std::cout << "Public member in Child: " << obj.getPublicMember() << std::endl;

    // obj.publicMember = 100; // Error: Cannot access public member directly from outside the class or derived classes

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, `Child` inherits `protected`ly from `Base`. Therefore, the `publicMember` of `Base` becomes a `protected` member in `Child`. The `publicMember` can be accessed within methods of `Child`, but not from outside, as attempting to access `publicMember` directly in the `main` function results in an error.
